1
00:00:57,640 --> 00:01:01,227
<i>There was a demon that lived in the air.</i>

2
00:01:01,477 --> 00:01:06,732
<i>They said whoever challenged him
would die.</i>

3
00:01:06,982 --> 00:01:08,859
<i>Their controls would freeze up.</i>

4
00:01:09,109 --> 00:01:12,404
<i>Their planes would buffet wildly...</i>

5
00:01:12,654 --> 00:01:16,199
<i>... and they would disintegrate.</i>

6
00:01:19,160 --> 00:01:22,330
<i>The demon lived at Mach 1 on the meter...</i>

7
00:01:22,580 --> 00:01:25,082
<i>... 750 miles an hour...</i>

8
00:01:25,333 --> 00:01:29,378
<i>... where the air could no longer
move out of the way.</i>

9
00:01:29,628 --> 00:01:36,468
<i>He lived behind a barrier through
which they said no man could ever pass.</i>

10
00:01:36,677 --> 00:01:41,723
<i>They called it the sound barrier.</i>

11
00:01:42,682 --> 00:01:44,601
<i>Then they built a small plane...</i>

12
00:01:44,851 --> 00:01:49,230
<i>... the X-1, to try and break
the sound barrier.</i>

13
00:01:49,480 --> 00:01:55,403
<i>And men came to the high desert
of California to ride it.</i>

14
00:01:57,697 --> 00:02:01,742
<i>They were called test pilots...</i>

15
00:02:01,867 --> 00:02:05,829
<i>... and no one knew their names.</i>

16
00:02:20,051 --> 00:02:22,929
<i>Okay, Whiskey Kilo 28, prepare to drop.</i>

17
00:02:23,179 --> 00:02:25,848
<i>Roger, Ground Control.
This is Whiskey Kilo 28...</i>

18
00:02:26,098 --> 00:02:30,102
<i>... lowering and launching... now.</i>

19
00:02:40,904 --> 00:02:44,449
<i>Mach .92.</i>

20
00:02:46,409 --> 00:02:49,954
<i>.93.</i>

21
00:02:51,747 --> 00:02:53,916
<i>.94.</i>

22
00:02:54,166 --> 00:02:57,795
<i>Hit a mild buffet there.</i>

23
00:02:58,420 --> 00:03:01,632
<i>Mach.95.</i>

24
00:03:14,769 --> 00:03:17,647
<i>.98!</i>

25
00:03:19,732 --> 00:03:22,318
<i>.99!</i>

26
00:03:22,568 --> 00:03:25,487
<i>WK 28, do you want
to declare an emergency?</i>

27
00:03:25,738 --> 00:03:29,783
<i>Negative. WK 28 is not...</i>

28
00:03:54,598 --> 00:03:57,976
Go away.

29
00:04:07,777 --> 00:04:10,655
"Lord, guard and guide

30
00:04:10,905 --> 00:04:14,325
The men who fly

31
00:04:14,575 --> 00:04:18,287
Through the great spaces

32
00:04:18,537 --> 00:04:22,541
In the sky."

33
00:04:22,625 --> 00:04:26,378
"Be with them always

34
00:04:26,628 --> 00:04:29,423
In the air

35
00:04:29,673 --> 00:04:36,262
In darkening storms or sunlight fair."

36
00:04:39,140 --> 00:04:45,771
"Hear us when we lift our prayer

37
00:04:47,189 --> 00:04:52,111
For all in peril

38
00:04:52,361 --> 00:04:57,449
In the air."

39
00:07:47,859 --> 00:07:50,070
I was looking at the pictures on your wall.

40
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:51,780
How come a fancy pilot...

41
00:07:52,030 --> 00:07:55,742
...like Slick there,
doesn't have his picture up there?

42
00:07:55,992 --> 00:07:58,661
What do you have to do
to get your picture up there?

43
00:07:58,911 --> 00:08:02,331
You have to die.

44
00:08:04,375 --> 00:08:07,503
Well, Yeager, you old bastard.

45
00:08:07,753 --> 00:08:12,633
Don't just stand in the doorway
like some lonesome sheepherder.

46
00:08:12,883 --> 00:08:14,843
Get your ass over here and have a drink.

47
00:08:15,093 --> 00:08:18,263
I got you something.

48
00:08:27,397 --> 00:08:28,981
You could be the first.

49
00:08:29,232 --> 00:08:32,485
The man who breaks the sound barrier
will be on top.

50
00:08:32,735 --> 00:08:34,195
You'd be the one they remembered.

51
00:08:34,445 --> 00:08:38,490
You're the best civilian pilot around.

52
00:08:38,741 --> 00:08:41,827
You get that helmet?

53
00:08:43,412 --> 00:08:44,746
It might work.

54
00:08:44,996 --> 00:08:46,706
I'll look like the Galloping Ghost in it.

55
00:08:46,957 --> 00:08:50,585
Some people say the sound barrier
can't be broke.

56
00:08:50,835 --> 00:08:53,296
An engineer will tell you it's an absolute...

57
00:08:53,546 --> 00:08:56,049
...like the firmness of the earth.

58
00:08:56,299 --> 00:08:59,510
The sound barrier is a farm
you can buy in the sky.

59
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:02,763
The controls will freeze up.
You can't budge the stick.

60
00:09:03,013 --> 00:09:07,309
Anybody tries to break it will auger in.

61
00:09:07,768 --> 00:09:11,355
Well now, maybe it can't be broke.

62
00:09:11,605 --> 00:09:14,024
Then again...

63
00:09:14,274 --> 00:09:17,319
...maybe it can.

64
00:09:17,569 --> 00:09:23,324
Maybe it can only be broke
for a specified sum.

65
00:09:23,574 --> 00:09:26,327
How much?

66
00:09:27,119 --> 00:09:29,747
$150,000.

67
00:09:29,997 --> 00:09:34,126
Come on, Slick, give us a break.

68
00:09:34,293 --> 00:09:38,505
Non-negotiable, as usual.

69
00:09:42,634 --> 00:09:44,052
What do we do now?

70
00:09:44,302 --> 00:09:46,554
That guy in the corner...

71
00:09:46,805 --> 00:09:48,098
Yeager is his name.

72
00:09:48,348 --> 00:09:51,559
He's some kind of a war hero.
Shot down five Germans in one day.

73
00:09:51,809 --> 00:09:54,395
He's a natural-born stick-and-rudder man.

74
00:09:54,645 --> 00:09:58,065
As press-liaison man for the Air Force,
I think...

75
00:09:58,315 --> 00:10:00,234
Any problems with him?

76
00:10:00,484 --> 00:10:02,403
- Only one.
- What's that?

77
00:10:02,653 --> 00:10:05,697
Holding him back.

78
00:10:12,996 --> 00:10:17,750
We were just talking to Slick
about the sound barrier.

79
00:10:18,001 --> 00:10:20,628
We feel that the X-1
is ready to have a go at it.

80
00:10:20,878 --> 00:10:24,715
We think the X-1's got the answer
to go beyond Mach 1.

81
00:10:24,966 --> 00:10:28,219
If there is any beyond.

82
00:10:29,470 --> 00:10:31,972
So, what do you think?

83
00:10:32,222 --> 00:10:35,892
I'll tell you. Half these engineers
have never been off the ground.

84
00:10:36,143 --> 00:10:39,479
They might tell you that
the sound barrier's a brick wall.

85
00:10:39,729 --> 00:10:42,732
It'll rip your ears off
if you try to go through it.

86
00:10:42,983 --> 00:10:46,236
If you ask me,
I don't believe the damn thing even exists.

87
00:10:46,486 --> 00:10:48,488
Waitress, a drink for Mr. Yeager.

88
00:10:48,738 --> 00:10:50,948
No thanks, I got one.

89
00:10:51,199 --> 00:10:53,909
So, do you think
you want to have a go at it?

90
00:10:54,160 --> 00:10:55,578
I might.

91
00:10:55,828 --> 00:11:01,125
But since, as you say,
this sound barrier doesn't really exist...

92
00:11:01,375 --> 00:11:02,584
...how much...

93
00:11:02,835 --> 00:11:04,920
How much you got?

94
00:11:05,170 --> 00:11:10,008
Just joking.
The Air Force is already paying me. Right?

95
00:11:10,675 --> 00:11:12,927
So when do we go?

96
00:11:13,178 --> 00:11:15,722
How about tomorrow morning?

97
00:11:15,972 --> 00:11:17,932
I'll be there.

98
00:11:18,182 --> 00:11:21,269
See you there.

99
00:11:22,853 --> 00:11:24,939
How much are you paying him?

100
00:11:25,189 --> 00:11:27,775
I think it's $283.

101
00:11:28,025 --> 00:11:29,026
A week?

102
00:11:29,276 --> 00:11:30,944
A month.

103
00:11:31,195 --> 00:11:34,322
Well, that's not bad.

104
00:11:38,118 --> 00:11:40,745
First fellow to break the sound barrier...

105
00:11:40,995 --> 00:11:45,416
...gets a free steak with all the trimmings.

106
00:11:46,667 --> 00:11:50,588
I'll have mine medium rare, please.

107
00:11:56,969 --> 00:12:01,431
Honey, you ever been caught
on the desert alone?

108
00:12:04,476 --> 00:12:07,520
I never have.

109
00:12:08,396 --> 00:12:11,941
I don't think I ever will.

110
00:12:12,984 --> 00:12:15,987
Never met the man
who could catch me out there.

111
00:12:16,237 --> 00:12:19,281
I'm half jackrabbit.

112
00:12:21,033 --> 00:12:23,410
Forget it, flyboy.

113
00:12:23,661 --> 00:12:26,663
You'd never catch me.

114
00:12:26,914 --> 00:12:29,666
I believe I will.

115
00:12:29,916 --> 00:12:33,128
Can't be done.

116
00:12:50,936 --> 00:12:54,481
Could I ask you something?

117
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:57,693
Forget it, sweetie.

118
00:12:57,943 --> 00:13:00,987
She's his wife.

119
00:13:19,630 --> 00:13:23,258
Glennis! I'm gonna get you!

120
00:13:24,009 --> 00:13:27,095
Come back here!

121
00:14:51,425 --> 00:14:54,845
What have you two been up to?

122
00:14:55,095 --> 00:14:56,680
Where's Ridley?

123
00:14:56,930 --> 00:15:00,308
Over there waiting on you.

124
00:15:03,436 --> 00:15:06,480
Can I talk to you?

125
00:15:08,107 --> 00:15:11,986
I got a little problem.

126
00:15:12,278 --> 00:15:16,073
A horse threw me last night
and I dinged up my goddamn ribs.

127
00:15:16,323 --> 00:15:17,199
How bad?

128
00:15:17,449 --> 00:15:20,869
I feel like I broke a couple
of the sons of bitches.

129
00:15:21,119 --> 00:15:24,706
I won't be able to lean over
to shut the door. Got any ideas?

130
00:15:24,956 --> 00:15:28,001
Your left side okay?

131
00:15:28,585 --> 00:15:32,380
I don't want these guys to know.
They'll find somebody else to fly this thing.

132
00:15:32,630 --> 00:15:36,092
I'll try to fix you a handle.

133
00:15:43,015 --> 00:15:45,225
Can you help me out?
I got a small emergency.

134
00:15:45,475 --> 00:15:51,273
I need to borrow your broom handle.
Just hold this right here.

135
00:15:58,821 --> 00:16:01,949
I think that'll work.

136
00:16:15,504 --> 00:16:18,423
Punch a hole in the sky.

137
00:16:18,673 --> 00:16:21,718
I'll be right back.

138
00:16:25,763 --> 00:16:26,931
How are you feeling?

139
00:16:27,181 --> 00:16:30,309
Oh, just about right.

140
00:17:30,241 --> 00:17:35,162
There she is, partner.
All bridled, saddled and ready to go.

141
00:17:35,412 --> 00:17:37,081
You got any Beemans?

142
00:17:37,331 --> 00:17:38,832
Yeah, I got a stick.

143
00:17:39,082 --> 00:17:40,959
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

144
00:17:41,209 --> 00:17:43,962
Fair enough.

145
00:17:57,058 --> 00:18:01,562
Stick this in the handle.
Take your good arm and just whang it.

146
00:18:01,812 --> 00:18:04,857
Okay, thanks, buddy.

147
00:19:23,931 --> 00:19:25,891
<i>Pre-drop checklist complete.</i>

148
00:19:26,141 --> 00:19:29,520
<i>Ten... nine...</i>

149
00:19:38,403 --> 00:19:40,989
<i>Drop!</i>

150
00:19:43,116 --> 00:19:46,285
<i>There you go, buddy.</i>

151
00:19:49,247 --> 00:19:53,042
<i>Put your spurs to her, Chuck.</i>

152
00:20:17,732 --> 00:20:21,068
<i>Mach.91.</i>

153
00:20:37,208 --> 00:20:39,836
<i>.92.</i>

154
00:20:43,297 --> 00:20:46,259
<i>.93.</i>

155
00:20:50,387 --> 00:20:52,056
<i>Hit a mild buffet there.</i>

156
00:20:52,306 --> 00:20:55,684
<i>Just the usual instability.</i>

157
00:20:55,726 --> 00:20:58,228
<i>Ridley, make a note here,
would you, if you got...</i>

158
00:20:58,478 --> 00:21:03,275
<i>... nothing better to do.
Elevator effectiveness regained.</i>

159
00:21:09,739 --> 00:21:12,950
<i>.95.</i>

160
00:21:15,077 --> 00:21:18,247
<i>.96.</i>

161
00:21:22,668 --> 00:21:24,795
<i>More buffeting.</i>

162
00:21:25,045 --> 00:21:26,255
<i>More commotion.</i>

163
00:21:26,505 --> 00:21:29,633
<i>Getting wobbly here.</i>

164
00:21:32,177 --> 00:21:34,137
<i>.98.</i>

165
00:21:34,387 --> 00:21:37,682
<i>She's getting real active.</i>

166
00:21:45,398 --> 00:21:48,108
<i>.99!</i>

167
00:21:57,576 --> 00:22:00,620
What's that sound?

168
00:22:05,667 --> 00:22:09,045
He bought the farm.

169
00:22:10,129 --> 00:22:14,049
That's it. We're back to square one.

170
00:22:15,050 --> 00:22:17,845
Wait a minute.

171
00:22:24,101 --> 00:22:27,270
<i>Ridley, make another note, would you?</i>

172
00:22:27,521 --> 00:22:29,856
<i>Must be something wrong
with the Machmeter.</i>

173
00:22:30,106 --> 00:22:32,358
<i>Jumped plumb off the scale.</i>

174
00:22:32,609 --> 00:22:34,360
<i>Gone screwy on me.</i>

175
00:22:34,611 --> 00:22:36,738
<i>You bust it, we'll fix it.</i>

176
00:22:36,988 --> 00:22:41,033
<i>Personally, I think you're seeing things.</i>

177
00:22:42,118 --> 00:22:47,331
<i>Could be. I'm still going upstairs
like a bat out of hell.</i>

178
00:22:50,626 --> 00:22:52,377
We did it!

179
00:22:52,627 --> 00:22:55,380
We finally broke the sound barrier.

180
00:22:55,630 --> 00:22:58,508
We did it!

181
00:23:34,792 --> 00:23:37,545
I want to place a long-distance call
to Los Angeles.

182
00:23:37,795 --> 00:23:39,046
Who are you calling?

183
00:23:39,296 --> 00:23:40,214
The press!

184
00:23:40,464 --> 00:23:43,801
This is big news.
The sound barrier's been broken.

185
00:23:44,051 --> 00:23:45,886
No, sir. No press.

186
00:23:46,136 --> 00:23:48,722
No word of this goes beyond the flight line.

187
00:23:48,972 --> 00:23:52,642
What's going on? This is big news.
We need coverage of this.

188
00:23:52,893 --> 00:23:54,644
No, sir. Sorry, no press.

189
00:23:54,894 --> 00:23:57,230
Those are orders. National security.

190
00:23:57,480 --> 00:23:59,065
But the war's over!

191
00:23:59,315 --> 00:24:02,568
Look, pal, maybe they don't want
someone to know.

192
00:24:02,819 --> 00:24:03,986
Who?

193
00:24:04,237 --> 00:24:05,655
The Russians, maybe.

194
00:24:05,905 --> 00:24:08,157
But they're our allies!

195
00:24:08,407 --> 00:24:14,329
Well, anyway, someone figured it out
that way, and that's the way it is.

196
00:24:14,580 --> 00:24:16,832
Chuck, you're our man!

197
00:24:17,082 --> 00:24:18,625
You're the fastest man alive!

198
00:24:18,875 --> 00:24:20,627
We want you to fly more planes for us.

199
00:24:20,877 --> 00:24:23,838
We want you to fly all our planes!

200
00:24:24,089 --> 00:24:28,134
What you been doing, hedgehopping?

201
00:25:06,962 --> 00:25:08,505
Word will get out, Major.

202
00:25:08,756 --> 00:25:11,550
Maybe not to the press
or the general public.

203
00:25:11,800 --> 00:25:15,887
But soon, every fighter jock, rocket ace,
and rat-racer in the country...

204
00:25:16,138 --> 00:25:21,059
...will be headed this way, wanting
to push the outside of the envelope...

205
00:25:21,309 --> 00:25:25,855
...and get to the top of the pyramid.

206
00:25:50,670 --> 00:25:52,755
Edwards Air Force Base.

207
00:25:53,006 --> 00:25:54,841
This is the place to be, hon.

208
00:25:55,091 --> 00:26:00,096
They're going faster, farther
and higher here than anywhere else.

209
00:26:04,183 --> 00:26:06,268
I'll tell you something else, too.

210
00:26:06,518 --> 00:26:11,773
We'll climb right up that ladder,
just like we did at Langley.

211
00:26:12,023 --> 00:26:13,942
We?

212
00:26:14,192 --> 00:26:16,111
You mean you.

213
00:26:16,361 --> 00:26:18,279
Hon, we're a team!

214
00:26:18,530 --> 00:26:20,907
I move up, you move up.

215
00:26:21,157 --> 00:26:24,952
Right to the top of the old pyramid.

216
00:26:25,203 --> 00:26:26,287
Slow down, Gordo.

217
00:26:26,537 --> 00:26:28,789
Come on now, you're scaring the girls.

218
00:26:29,039 --> 00:26:33,752
You're scaring the girls. You are!

219
00:26:37,547 --> 00:26:41,593
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

220
00:26:42,052 --> 00:26:45,764
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

221
00:26:50,727 --> 00:26:54,272
You're looking at him, baby.

222
00:26:56,899 --> 00:26:59,151
Come on, cheer up.

223
00:26:59,401 --> 00:27:03,572
Hey, have I ever let you down?

224
00:29:59,613 --> 00:30:02,741
Deke, that's 62 men...

225
00:30:02,991 --> 00:30:06,494
...in the last 36 weeks.

226
00:30:06,619 --> 00:30:10,081
You know what that averages?

227
00:30:12,083 --> 00:30:15,711
Is that Gus Grissom from Langley Field?

228
00:30:15,961 --> 00:30:18,797
What is an ace like you
doing in a place like this?

229
00:30:19,048 --> 00:30:21,884
Well, if it ain't Hot Dog.

230
00:30:22,134 --> 00:30:24,094
Gordo...

231
00:30:24,344 --> 00:30:26,555
...Cooper, right?
- Yeah.

232
00:30:26,805 --> 00:30:30,892
Gordo thinks he's one of those
hot-dog pilots you hear so much about.

233
00:30:31,142 --> 00:30:32,894
You got a short memory.

234
00:30:33,144 --> 00:30:37,815
I am not one of them hot-dog pilots.
I am the Hot Dog Man himself.

235
00:30:38,065 --> 00:30:43,654
I guess you're too shy to tell this guy
how I used to wax your tail.

236
00:30:44,780 --> 00:30:47,658
Wax my tail?

237
00:30:47,950 --> 00:30:50,869
Hot Dog, you were just in my shadow.

238
00:30:51,119 --> 00:30:53,121
That's where you'll always be.

239
00:30:53,372 --> 00:30:56,708
What are you two rookies going to have?

240
00:30:56,958 --> 00:30:59,502
Rookies?

241
00:31:00,295 --> 00:31:02,880
Now hold on, sis.

242
00:31:03,131 --> 00:31:07,593
You are looking
at a whole new ballgame here now.

243
00:31:07,843 --> 00:31:10,596
In a few years I bet you're even
going to immortalize us...

244
00:31:10,846 --> 00:31:15,267
...by putting our pictures up there
on your wall.

245
00:31:19,479 --> 00:31:22,024
Did I say something wrong?

246
00:31:22,274 --> 00:31:26,069
I'll tell you. We got two categories
of pilots around here.

247
00:31:26,319 --> 00:31:29,531
We got your prime pilots
that get all the hot planes.

248
00:31:29,781 --> 00:31:34,660
And we got your pudknockers
who dream about getting the hot planes.

249
00:31:34,911 --> 00:31:39,665
Now what are you two pudknockers
going to have?

250
00:31:43,335 --> 00:31:46,213
Scotch.

251
00:31:46,672 --> 00:31:49,341
You know what happened!
The machine broke.

252
00:31:49,591 --> 00:31:50,675
Not the machine, it's the man.

253
00:31:50,926 --> 00:31:55,889
He was dead before he went up.
Don't talk about it here.

254
00:32:15,199 --> 00:32:19,077
Good one. Now fire it in here.

255
00:32:19,077 --> 00:32:21,121
Look at old Yeager.

256
00:32:21,371 --> 00:32:25,125
On top of the pyramid
for five goddamn years.

257
00:32:25,375 --> 00:32:29,462
Every time somebody goes faster,
he just goes up again.

258
00:32:29,712 --> 00:32:33,591
He stays the fastest man alive.

259
00:32:37,511 --> 00:32:39,221
You know...

260
00:32:39,471 --> 00:32:41,390
...sometimes...

261
00:32:41,640 --> 00:32:46,436
...all it takes is just the sound
of a truck starting.

262
00:32:46,520 --> 00:32:48,146
I think:

263
00:32:48,396 --> 00:32:51,650
"That's the crash truck."

264
00:32:56,904 --> 00:32:58,489
Anyway...

265
00:32:58,740 --> 00:33:01,325
...I'm really glad we could talk.

266
00:33:01,576 --> 00:33:06,247
I thought I was the only one
who had these nightmares.

267
00:33:06,288 --> 00:33:08,123
Yeah, me too.

268
00:33:08,374 --> 00:33:11,835
Nobody ever wants to talk
about anything around here.

269
00:33:12,085 --> 00:33:15,172
Everybody's always trying to...

270
00:33:15,422 --> 00:33:19,801
..."maintain an even strain".

271
00:33:19,926 --> 00:33:25,932
Well, you marry a fighter jock
and you marry the military.

272
00:33:25,932 --> 00:33:27,850
I'll tell you one thing.

273
00:33:28,100 --> 00:33:30,978
The military owes me for all this.

274
00:33:31,228 --> 00:33:35,316
One day I expect the military
to make good.

275
00:33:38,777 --> 00:33:43,198
Well, it sure ain't your average dull life.

276
00:33:43,448 --> 00:33:45,158
I went East for a reunion...

277
00:33:45,408 --> 00:33:48,620
...and all my friends could talk about
was their husbands' work.

278
00:33:48,870 --> 00:33:54,000
How dog-eat-dog and cutthroat it was
on Madison Avenue...

279
00:33:54,250 --> 00:33:57,336
...places like that.

280
00:33:58,963 --> 00:34:02,174
Cutthroat?

281
00:34:02,466 --> 00:34:05,886
I wondered how they would have felt...

282
00:34:06,136 --> 00:34:09,389
...if each time their husband
went in to make a deal...

283
00:34:09,640 --> 00:34:15,145
...there was a one in four chance
he wouldn't come out of the meeting.

284
00:34:18,606 --> 00:34:22,985
I'm going home to my folks in San Diego.

285
00:34:24,695 --> 00:34:27,114
What did Gordo say?

286
00:34:27,365 --> 00:34:31,410
He "maintained an even strain".

287
00:34:35,706 --> 00:34:38,458
Look at them.

288
00:34:38,542 --> 00:34:42,671
You'd think they were talking about sports.

289
00:34:48,218 --> 00:34:50,345
Men...

290
00:34:50,595 --> 00:34:55,266
Sometimes they're just such... assholes.

291
00:35:06,902 --> 00:35:10,155
Sometimes they sure are
handy assholes, though.

292
00:35:10,405 --> 00:35:13,408
Yeah, sometimes...

293
00:35:14,159 --> 00:35:17,120
Sometimes.

294
00:35:20,289 --> 00:35:23,417
You want a hot dog?

295
00:35:28,255 --> 00:35:31,800
I'm leaving, Gordo.

296
00:35:36,763 --> 00:35:38,348
Look at that!

297
00:35:38,598 --> 00:35:41,351
Yeah, that's the D-558 Phase 2.

298
00:35:41,601 --> 00:35:43,019
Scott Crossfield.

299
00:35:43,269 --> 00:35:47,482
It sure as hell is. Jesus!

300
00:35:49,275 --> 00:35:52,903
He scorched that one, didn't he?

301
00:35:54,947 --> 00:35:57,032
He's pushing the outside of the envelope.

302
00:35:57,283 --> 00:35:59,118
He must be going for a record.

303
00:35:59,368 --> 00:36:03,080
He's shooting for Mach 2, I heard.

304
00:36:04,498 --> 00:36:08,835
<i>On the 50th anniversary
of the Wright Brothers' historic flight...</i>

305
00:36:09,085 --> 00:36:12,630
<i>... another historic flight takes place,
as Scott Crossfield...</i>

306
00:36:12,881 --> 00:36:16,884
<i>... streaks across the skies
over the high desert in California.</i>

307
00:36:17,135 --> 00:36:18,135
<i>Mach 2.</i>

308
00:36:18,386 --> 00:36:21,222
<i>Almost 1,500 miles per hour...</i>

309
00:36:21,472 --> 00:36:23,891
<i>... and a new world record!</i>

310
00:36:24,141 --> 00:36:26,393
<i>It's a field day for the press.</i>

311
00:36:26,643 --> 00:36:28,979
<i>Congratulations come
from a previous record holder...</i>

312
00:36:29,229 --> 00:36:34,025
<i>... as he shakes the hand
of the fastest man alive, Scott Crossfield.</i>

313
00:36:34,276 --> 00:36:37,237
<i>And there's a comradeship of speed.</i>

314
00:36:37,487 --> 00:36:42,116
To Scott Crossfield, the fastest man alive.

315
00:37:00,008 --> 00:37:03,720
Compliments of Pancho's, Scotty.

316
00:37:05,180 --> 00:37:07,265
The real test wasn't Mach 2.

317
00:37:07,515 --> 00:37:12,645
I guess that demon lives out
at about 2.3 on your Machmeter.

318
00:37:12,895 --> 00:37:15,606
Yeah, but Mach 2 was the magic number.

319
00:37:15,856 --> 00:37:20,736
Like 60 homers, like batting.400,
like the four-minute mile.

320
00:37:20,986 --> 00:37:23,113
The press likes a nice round number.

321
00:37:23,364 --> 00:37:26,450
After that, they don't care,
until the next magic number.

322
00:37:26,700 --> 00:37:30,370
You need more than speed records.
You need coverage.

323
00:37:30,620 --> 00:37:31,955
Coverage?

324
00:37:32,205 --> 00:37:35,792
You mean them root weevils
that crawl around popping off cameras?

325
00:37:36,042 --> 00:37:38,211
Those root weevils write history.

326
00:37:38,461 --> 00:37:43,883
Let them write the history,
and let the pilots fly the planes.

327
00:37:44,050 --> 00:37:46,761
Pilots.

328
00:38:09,699 --> 00:38:12,243
You know what really makes
your rocket ships go up?

329
00:38:12,493 --> 00:38:15,996
The aerodynamics would take
so long to explain to you that...

330
00:38:16,247 --> 00:38:17,122
Funding.

331
00:38:17,373 --> 00:38:19,291
That's what makes your ships go up.

332
00:38:19,541 --> 00:38:21,543
I'll tell you something.

333
00:38:21,794 --> 00:38:23,712
And you guys, too.

334
00:38:23,962 --> 00:38:27,007
No bucks, no Buck Rogers.

335
00:38:27,257 --> 00:38:29,718
Whoever gets the funding
gets the technology.

336
00:38:29,968 --> 00:38:32,762
Whoever gets the technology stays on top.

337
00:38:33,012 --> 00:38:35,265
Flyboy, let's dance.

338
00:38:35,515 --> 00:38:38,643
I'll drink to that.

339
00:39:09,630 --> 00:39:12,591
He'll be going after Crossfield soon,
won't he?

340
00:39:12,842 --> 00:39:14,009
No, he won't.

341
00:39:14,260 --> 00:39:19,139
He'll be going after that demon
that lives in the thin air.

342
00:39:58,134 --> 00:39:59,719
You got any Beemans?

343
00:39:59,969 --> 00:40:03,556
Even before you hit Mach 2,
she'll be unforgiving on you.

344
00:40:03,806 --> 00:40:06,475
So take it easy.
Wring her out a little bit this time.

345
00:40:06,726 --> 00:40:07,643
You got any gum?

346
00:40:07,893 --> 00:40:08,936
Yeah, I got me a stick.

347
00:40:09,186 --> 00:40:11,814
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

348
00:40:12,064 --> 00:40:15,275
- Fair enough.
- Thank you.

349
00:40:29,497 --> 00:40:30,915
<i>Okay, drop her.</i>

350
00:40:31,165 --> 00:40:34,877
All right, here we go again.

351
00:40:37,588 --> 00:40:40,049
Drop!

352
00:40:49,099 --> 00:40:52,352
<i>Number 3 coming on.</i>

353
00:40:59,025 --> 00:41:03,237
<i>Got seven seconds on 150 right now.</i>

354
00:41:21,379 --> 00:41:23,756
<i>I've got you in sight, Chuck.</i>

355
00:41:24,007 --> 00:41:25,967
<i>Going out of sight...</i>

356
00:41:26,217 --> 00:41:28,761
<i>... now!</i>

357
00:41:34,016 --> 00:41:36,894
<i>Mach 1.</i>

358
00:41:45,861 --> 00:41:48,488
<i>Number 4.</i>

359
00:41:52,116 --> 00:41:53,785
<i>Here goes Mach 2.</i>

360
00:41:54,035 --> 00:41:55,203
<i>2. 1.</i>

361
00:41:55,453 --> 00:41:58,331
<i>Sorry, Scotty.</i>

362
00:41:58,456 --> 00:41:59,707
<i>You got her now, buddy.</i>

363
00:41:59,957 --> 00:42:02,293
<i>You can ease it back.</i>

364
00:42:02,543 --> 00:42:03,794
<i>Bring it on in.</i>

365
00:42:04,044 --> 00:42:06,880
<i>I'm pushing the envelope.</i>

366
00:42:07,131 --> 00:42:10,467
<i>See where that demon lives.</i>

367
00:42:29,318 --> 00:42:32,863
<i>Come in, Chuck.</i>

368
00:42:33,364 --> 00:42:34,656
<i>Say again. Over.</i>

369
00:42:34,907 --> 00:42:38,327
<i>Do you read? Over.</i>

370
00:42:39,244 --> 00:42:42,455
<i>Damn! He's uncorked it!</i>

371
00:42:42,706 --> 00:42:43,999
<i>Mayday! Mayday!</i>

372
00:42:44,249 --> 00:42:47,627
<i>Alert all ground crews.</i>

373
00:42:50,755 --> 00:42:53,966
<i>Talk to me!</i>

374
00:42:59,263 --> 00:43:01,807
<i>Come in!</i>

375
00:43:03,017 --> 00:43:06,562
<i>Do you read me? Over.</i>

376
00:43:16,654 --> 00:43:19,991
<i>I'm fighting bad here.</i>

377
00:43:20,283 --> 00:43:24,996
<i>I'm down to 25,000 over Tehachapi.</i>

378
00:43:27,123 --> 00:43:31,043
<i>I don't know if I can make it
back to base or not.</i>

379
00:43:31,293 --> 00:43:32,503
<i>What happened?</i>

380
00:43:32,753 --> 00:43:35,547
<i>Think I bust the canopy with my head.</i>

381
00:43:35,797 --> 00:43:38,925
<i>I'm getting okay now.</i>

382
00:43:40,135 --> 00:43:43,888
<i>We sure chased that old demon this time.</i>

383
00:43:44,139 --> 00:43:47,725
<i>That's as fast as a man can go.</i>

384
00:43:48,142 --> 00:43:51,354
<i>What's next, Ridley?</i>

385
00:44:29,723 --> 00:44:30,807
It's called Sputnik.

386
00:44:31,058 --> 00:44:34,561
We know. Sit down.

387
00:44:38,857 --> 00:44:41,359
And as I was saying...

388
00:44:41,609 --> 00:44:45,530
...whoever controls
the high ground of space...

389
00:44:45,780 --> 00:44:48,074
...will control the world.

390
00:44:48,324 --> 00:44:52,578
The Roman Empire controlled
the world because it could build roads.

391
00:44:52,828 --> 00:44:57,791
Later, the British Empire was dominant
because it had ships.

392
00:44:58,041 --> 00:45:03,171
In the air stage, we were powerful
because we had the airplane.

393
00:45:03,421 --> 00:45:07,217
Now the Communists have established
a foothold in outer space.

394
00:45:07,467 --> 00:45:10,845
Soon they'll have space platforms
to drop nuclear bombs on us...

395
00:45:11,095 --> 00:45:13,681
...like rocks from a highway overpass.

396
00:45:13,931 --> 00:45:16,809
How the hell did they get ahead of us?

397
00:45:17,059 --> 00:45:20,646
Gentlemen, I think we're ready.

398
00:45:24,691 --> 00:45:28,820
Is there a loose plug over there anywhere?

399
00:45:30,030 --> 00:45:31,698
Here it is. I'll get it.

400
00:45:31,948 --> 00:45:34,701
Senator Johnson's right.
This is Armageddon.

401
00:45:34,951 --> 00:45:37,704
The decisive battle between
the forces of good and evil.

402
00:45:37,954 --> 00:45:42,333
We're engaged in a struggle for survival.

403
00:45:43,209 --> 00:45:45,503
This footage was assembled from...

404
00:45:45,753 --> 00:45:49,673
...sources operating under deep cover
at great risk.

405
00:45:49,924 --> 00:45:53,177
We're fortunate this material
did not perish with a couple of men.

406
00:45:53,427 --> 00:45:56,513
This is secret footage
of the Russian Korabl rocket...

407
00:45:56,763 --> 00:46:00,475
...and these are the German scientists
that they captured after the war.

408
00:46:00,725 --> 00:46:05,438
Was it their German scientists
who got them up there first?

409
00:46:05,772 --> 00:46:07,315
No, it was not, Senator.

410
00:46:07,565 --> 00:46:10,651
Our Germans are better
than their Germans.

411
00:46:10,902 --> 00:46:13,904
That's Titov on the right
and on the left is Gagarin.

412
00:46:14,155 --> 00:46:18,534
No, Titov's on the left.
Gagarin's on the right.

413
00:46:18,784 --> 00:46:21,120
They bear a great resemblance
to each other.

414
00:46:21,370 --> 00:46:25,916
If the Soviets ever do put a man up there,
it will be one of these two.

415
00:46:26,166 --> 00:46:28,001
Most likely, the one on the left.

416
00:46:28,251 --> 00:46:31,129
- Gagarin.
- Titov.

417
00:46:31,171 --> 00:46:32,589
Isn't that their chief designer?

418
00:46:32,839 --> 00:46:34,257
We know very little about him.

419
00:46:34,507 --> 00:46:36,926
- Let us see him again.
- Here's some more of him.

420
00:46:37,176 --> 00:46:40,096
They've developed a program
of stupendous dimensions...

421
00:46:40,346 --> 00:46:44,475
...and he is clearly the genius behind it.

422
00:46:44,934 --> 00:46:47,603
I, for one, do not intend to go to sleep...

423
00:46:47,853 --> 00:46:51,732
...by the light of a Communist moon.

424
00:46:53,942 --> 00:46:57,654
Get that moron off of there!

425
00:47:00,198 --> 00:47:02,867
We could have orbited
a satellite a year ago...

426
00:47:03,117 --> 00:47:05,078
...if we had been given a green light.

427
00:47:05,328 --> 00:47:08,956
Now we must get something up there
quick and dirty, any way at all.

428
00:47:09,207 --> 00:47:10,458
Well, what?

429
00:47:10,708 --> 00:47:14,670
By combining our available rockets,
the Redstone, the Atlas...

430
00:47:14,920 --> 00:47:18,048
...I agree that we could launch a pod.

431
00:47:18,298 --> 00:47:19,299
A pot?

432
00:47:19,550 --> 00:47:20,801
A pod.

433
00:47:21,051 --> 00:47:22,219
A capsule.

434
00:47:22,469 --> 00:47:25,055
Now, we will be in full control of this pod.

435
00:47:25,305 --> 00:47:27,432
It will go up like a cannonball...

436
00:47:27,682 --> 00:47:30,310
...and come down like a cannonball...

437
00:47:30,560 --> 00:47:33,021
...splashing down in the ocean...

438
00:47:33,271 --> 00:47:37,483
...with a parachute to spare the life
of the specimen inside.

439
00:47:37,733 --> 00:47:39,151
Spaceman?

440
00:47:39,402 --> 00:47:42,154
Specimen.

441
00:47:42,863 --> 00:47:46,617
Well, what kind of "specimen"?

442
00:47:46,617 --> 00:47:48,660
A tough one.

443
00:47:48,911 --> 00:47:51,788
Responsive to orders.

444
00:47:52,038 --> 00:47:54,082
I had in mind a jimp.

445
00:47:54,332 --> 00:47:55,333
"Jimp"?

446
00:47:55,583 --> 00:47:57,669
Well, what the hell is a "jimp"?

447
00:47:57,919 --> 00:48:01,756
A jimp. A jimpanzee, Senator. An ape.

448
00:48:02,006 --> 00:48:07,386
The first American into space
is not going to be a chimpanzee.

449
00:48:07,386 --> 00:48:10,139
Who would you put into space,
Mr. President?

450
00:48:10,389 --> 00:48:14,184
We have film of some people
we think are strong candidates.

451
00:48:14,435 --> 00:48:18,855
We'd like to run it by you
and stimulate some thinking.

452
00:48:19,106 --> 00:48:22,901
These are people we felt
would be excellent in the splashdown.

453
00:48:23,151 --> 00:48:24,861
We like the one on the right.

454
00:48:25,111 --> 00:48:28,364
- No, on the left.
- On the right. Don't embarrass me!

455
00:48:28,615 --> 00:48:33,202
These people are very experienced with
machinery and have their own helmets.

456
00:48:33,452 --> 00:48:34,579
Is that a factor?

457
00:48:34,829 --> 00:48:36,455
As you'll see...

458
00:48:36,706 --> 00:48:40,501
...they're quite comfortable
in conditions of flame.

459
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:46,632
Now this is personnel who have
very well-developed equilibrium.

460
00:48:46,757 --> 00:48:49,176
Good middle ear. Also very nice people.

461
00:48:49,426 --> 00:48:50,552
Very easy to work with.

462
00:48:50,802 --> 00:48:53,680
With some work,
they could be very responsive to orders.

463
00:48:53,930 --> 00:48:56,683
This is my first choice.
The man with the hood.

464
00:48:56,933 --> 00:49:01,521
Since he works without eyesight,
his other senses are sharpened.

465
00:49:01,771 --> 00:49:04,982
In space there'll be little need
for eyeballing at any rate.

466
00:49:05,232 --> 00:49:07,985
The cannonball effect you mentioned...

467
00:49:08,235 --> 00:49:10,863
We were basically thinking about...

468
00:49:11,113 --> 00:49:13,156
...putting a couple into orbit.

469
00:49:13,407 --> 00:49:16,034
Possibly adds emotional stability.

470
00:49:16,284 --> 00:49:19,537
This individual combines many
plus factors that we mentioned.

471
00:49:19,788 --> 00:49:23,708
Ease with flames, comfort at heights
and agility in the splashdown phase.

472
00:49:23,958 --> 00:49:27,879
Also, he is available as of the 15th.

473
00:49:28,713 --> 00:49:31,007
I want test pilots!

474
00:49:31,257 --> 00:49:33,300
Test pilots? No, you can't deal with them.

475
00:49:33,551 --> 00:49:36,679
I'm sure we can do better
with another type of man...

476
00:49:36,929 --> 00:49:38,681
...any other type of man.

477
00:49:38,931 --> 00:49:40,516
A more manageable type.

478
00:49:40,766 --> 00:49:42,601
It will only complicate things.

479
00:49:42,851 --> 00:49:45,228
With a man we must guarantee
a safe return.

480
00:49:45,479 --> 00:49:50,025
Mr. President, I think
you'd be wise to reconsider.

481
00:49:50,316 --> 00:49:51,401
Test pilots?

482
00:49:51,651 --> 00:49:53,236
We'll be heading for some air bases.

483
00:49:53,486 --> 00:49:55,113
Not just some air bases.

484
00:49:55,363 --> 00:49:59,867
The one with the great test pilots.
There's only one place to go.

485
00:50:00,117 --> 00:50:03,996
<i>I was there once before
and I hoped I'd never have to go back.</i>

486
00:50:04,246 --> 00:50:08,917
<i>It's a god-forsaken spot on the roof
of the high desert in California.</i>

487
00:50:09,168 --> 00:50:12,754
A prehistoric throwback
of an airfield called Edwards.

488
00:50:13,004 --> 00:50:15,840
They've got a weird, mad-monk squadron.

489
00:50:16,091 --> 00:50:18,593
They live in rat shacks, terrible conditions.

490
00:50:18,843 --> 00:50:22,680
Corrugated tin, bare bones, low rent.

491
00:50:22,930 --> 00:50:24,766
This is the joint they hang out in.

492
00:50:25,016 --> 00:50:27,268
Pancho's Happy Bottom Riding Club.

493
00:50:27,518 --> 00:50:29,937
It's called Happy Bottom Riding Club?

494
00:50:30,187 --> 00:50:32,398
How'd it get a name like that?

495
00:50:32,648 --> 00:50:35,567
Ask Pancho.

496
00:50:37,194 --> 00:50:40,489
We're meeting the Liaison Officer.
They are expecting us.

497
00:50:40,739 --> 00:50:42,324
They? Who's "they"?

498
00:50:42,574 --> 00:50:45,327
The best...

499
00:50:46,536 --> 00:50:49,539
The best test pilots in the world.

500
00:50:49,789 --> 00:50:52,875
They got some kind of brotherhood.

501
00:50:53,126 --> 00:50:55,127
They think they got the right stuff.

502
00:50:55,378 --> 00:50:57,630
What stuff? Heroism, bravery?

503
00:50:57,880 --> 00:50:59,632
